{"id":"1112.3333","submitter":"Greg Kuperberg","authors":"Greg Kuperberg (UC Davis)","title":"Another subexponential-time quantum algorithm for the dihedral hidden\n  subgroup problem","comments":"10 pages","journal-ref":"8th Conference on the Theory of Quantum Computation, Communication\n  and Cryptography 22 (2013), 20-34","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We give an algorithm for the hidden subgroup problem for the dihedral group\n$D_N$, or equivalently the cyclic hidden shift problem, that supersedes our\nfirst algorithm and is suggested by Regev's algorithm. It runs in\n$\\exp(O(\\sqrt{\\log N}))$ quantum time and uses $\\exp(O(\\sqrt{\\log N}))$\nclassical space, but only $O(\\log N)$ quantum space. The algorithm also runs\nfaster with quantumly addressable classical space than with fully classical\nspace. In the hidden shift form, which is more natural for this algorithm\nregardless, it can also make use of multiple hidden shifts. It can also be\nextended with two parameters that trade classical space and classical time for\nquantum time. At the extreme space-saving end, the algorithm becomes Regev's\nalgorithm. At the other end, if the algorithm is allowed classical memory with\nquantum random access, then many trade-offs between classical and quantum time\nare possible.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 14 Dec 2011 20:45:44 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-09-16"}
