{"id":"1112.3479","submitter":"Matthias Kuenzer","authors":"Matthias Kuenzer","title":"On adjoint functors of the Heller operator","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.KT math.RT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Given an abelian category A with enough projectives, we can form its stable\ncategory _A_ := A/Proj(A)$. The Heller operator Omega : _A_ -> _A_ is\ncharacterised on an object X by a choice of a short exact sequence Omega X -> P\n-> X in A with P projective. If A is Frobenius, then Omega is an equivalence,\nhence has a left and a right adjoint. If A is hereditary, then Omega is zero,\nhence has a left and a right adjoint. In general, Omega is neither an\nequivalence nor zero. In the examples we have calculated via Magma, it has a\nleft adjoint, but in general not a right adjoint. If A has projective covers,\nthen Omega preserves monomorphisms; this would also follow from Omega having a\nleft adjoint. I do not know an example where Omega does not have a left\nadjoint.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 15 Dec 2011 10:59:21 GMT"}],"update_date":"2011-12-16"}
