{"id":"1112.3546","submitter":"Sergei Sergeev","authors":"Sergei Sergeev","title":"An application of the max-plus spectral theory to an ultradiscrete\n  analogue of the Lax pair","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Tropical Geometry of Integrable Systems, vol. 580 of Contemporary\n  Mathematics, 2012, p. 117-133","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.RA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study the ultradiscrete analogue of Lax pair proposed by Willox et al.\nThis \"pair\" is a max-plus linear system comprising four equations. Our starting\npoint is to treat this system as a combination of two max-plus eigenproblems,\nwith two additional constraints. Though infinite-dimensional, these two\neigenproblems can be treated by means of the \"standard\" max-plus spectral\ntheory. In particular, any solution to the system can be described as a\nmax-linear combination of fundamental eigenvectors associated with each\nsoliton. We then describe the operation of undressing using pairs of\nfundamental eigenvectors. We also study the solvability of the complete system\nof four equations as proposed by Willox et al.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 15 Dec 2011 15:54:50 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 6 Jun 2012 16:04:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-01-16"}
{"id":"1112.3547","submitter":"Eugene Frumker","authors":"E. Frumker, G. G. Paulus, H. Niikura, A. Naumov, D. M. Villeneuve, and\n  P. B. Corkum","title":"Order-dependent structure of High Harmonic Wavefronts","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Optics Express 20 (2012) 13870-13877","doi":"10.1364/OE.20.013870","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.optics physics.atom-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The physics of high harmonics has led to the generation of attosecond pulses\nand to trains of attosecond pulses. Measurements that confirm the pulse\nduration are all performed in the far field. All pulse duration measurements\ntacitly assume that both the beam's wavefront and intensity profile are\nindependent of frequency. However, if one or both are frequency dependent, then\nthe retrieved pulse duration depends on the location where the measurement is\nmade. We measure that each harmonic is very close to a Gaussian, but we also\nfind that both the intensity profile and the beam wavefront depend\nsignificantly on the harmonic order.\n  Thus, our findings mean that the pulse duration will depend on where the\npulse is observed. Measurement of spectrally resolved wavefronts along with\ntemporal characterization at one single point in the beam would enable complete\nspace-time reconstruction of attosecond pulses. Future attosecond science\nexperiments need not be restricted to spatially averaged observables.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 15 Dec 2011 15:57:13 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-06-15"}
